**Nick St Aubyn**

Nicholas Francis St Aubyn (born 19 November 1955) is a [Conservative Party (/Conservative_Party_(UK))] politician in the [United Kingdom (/United_Kingdom)].  

Early life  

St Aubyn is the younger son of the Hon. Piers St Aubyn [MC](/Military_Cross) by his marriage to Mary Bailey‑Southwell, and a grandson of [Baron St Levan](/Baron_St_Levan). He was educated at [Eton College](/Eton_College) and [Trinity College, Oxford](/Trinity_College,_Oxford), where he belonged to the [Oxford University Liberal Club](/Oxford_University_Liberal_Club) and, in the wake of the 1975 referendum on UK EEC‑membership, served as President of the [Young European Federalists](/Young_European_Federalists). He earned a [Bachelor of Arts (/Bachelor_of_Arts)] in [PPE (/Philosophy,_Politics,_and_Economics)] in 1977; the degree was later upgraded to a [Master of Arts (/Master_of_Arts_(Oxford,_Cambridge,_and_Dublin))] (MA Oxon). Prior to Oxford he spent time in Soweto, South Africa, working for the Project Trust.  

His professional trajectory reads like a résumé of mid‑late‑20th‑century finance: a loan officer at Morgan Guaranty Trust (1977‑81), head of the London office of [Morgan Futures](/JPMorgan_Chase) (1981‑84), head of the [Sterling](/Pound_sterling) and [Arbitrage](/Arbitrage) [Swaps Desk](/Swaption) (1984‑86), Vice President of [Kleinwort Benson](/Kleinwort_Benson) Cross Finance (1986‑87), and a stint in the Financial Products Division of [American International Group](/American_International_Group) (1987‑89). From 1989‑93 he chaired Gemini Ltd., and from 1993‑97 he chaired Fitzroy Joinery Ltd in [Plymouth](/Plymouth).  

Political career  

Between 1982‑86 St Aubyn served as a Conservative councillor on [Westminster City Council](/Westminster_City_Council), representing the [Little Venice ward](/Little_Venice_(ward)). He contested the [Truro by‑election](/1987_Truro_by‑election) in March 1987 after the death of [David Penhaligon](/David_Penhaligon), subsequently fighting the [Truro](/Truro_(UK_Parliament_constituency)) seat at the 1987 general election and again at the 1992 election, each time narrowing the Liberal majority.  

Following the retirement of veteran Conservative MP [David Howell](/David_Howell,_Baron_Howell_of_Guildford), St Aubyn was selected as the party’s candidate for [Guildford](/Guildford_(UK_Parliament_constituency)) ahead of the 1997 general election. He held the seat through the Labour landslide, though with a reduced majority over the [Liberal Democrats](/Liberal_Democrats_(UK)), and narrowly lost it in 2001 to [Sue Doughty](/Sue_Doughty). During his parliamentary tenure he sat on the [Education Select Committee](/Education_Select_Committee) and acted as [Parliamentary Private Secretary](/Parliamentary_Private_Secretary) to [Michael Portillo](/Michael_Portillo). He opted not to stand in the 2005 election, which saw [Anne Milton](/Anne_Milton) reclaim the constituency for the Conservatives.  

Personal life  

St Aubyn married Jane Brooks in 1980; the couple has two sons (Henry and Edward) and three daughters (Kitty, Alice and Camilla). His elder brother inherited the family title [Lord St Levan](/Lord_St_Levan) from their uncle, the 4th Baron St Levan ([John St Aubyn, 4th Baron St Levan](/John_St_Aubyn,_4th_Baron_St_Levan)).  

Books  

He has authored *Custom of the County* (2010), a work that reflects his aristocratic roots and political interests.  

